Against the grain with Monty Bennett


















Opinions



 


                    Against the grain with Monty Bennett
                


                    18 JUNE 2013
                    6:11 AM
                



	Even though he heads a public company, Ashford Hospitality Trust Chairman and CEO Monty Bennett likes to go out on a limb.






By  Ed Watkins
ed.watkins550@gmail.com

@EdWatkins1





As CEO and chairman of the board of a public company, Ashford Hospitality Trust, Monty J. Bennett must be deliberate in what he says in public forums. But if you read between the lines, you can tell he’s someone who likes to take a chance or two. He calls it “going against the grain,” and he spoke about it during a panel discussion at the recent 35th Annual New York University International Hospitality Industry Investment Conference.

“In the public markets, there are only so many things you can do (that go) against the grain,” he said during a panel titled “CEO Optimism Reigns.” 

“We have an affiliated management company, so that goes a little bit against the grain. We like to make loans, in addition to investing in hotels, that’s a little bit against the grain. You do three or four of those things and investors say, ‘Stop.’”

Bennett showed he’s not reluctant to make an against-the-grain move with Ashford’s purchase last month of the 142-room Pier House Resort and Caribbean Spa in Key West, Florida, for $90 million, a whopping $634,000 per room. According to the company’s news release announcing the deal, the purchase represented a trailing 12-months capitalization rate of 6.2%.

During the NYU Investment Conference session, moderator Scott D. Berman, principal of PricewaterhouseCoopers’ hospitality and leisure practice*, questioned Ashford’s rationale for paying such a price for an independent hotel in one of the least accessible resort destinations in the United States.

Bennett didn’t miss a beat in defending the deal and, in fact, believes Ashford’s affiliated management company, Remington Hotels, will be able to add 35% to the Pier House’s bottom line in its first year of operating the hotel. Remington manages three other hotels in the market, and Bennett believes profit enhancement is possible through savings in payroll and insurance and additional revenues generated by charging for parking and adding a resort fee.

But Bennett is a real estate professional at heart, and that’s what drew him to the deal. He referred to Rate of Growth laws in Florida that govern development in the state, and the Florida Keys in particular. He said because of its location more than 100 miles from the mainland, Key West is subject to limitations on new infrastructure, such as water and electricity.



“The bottom line is you can’t build in Key West,” he said. “You can’t add more hotel rooms, so when you’re calculating what it would cost to replace those rooms (at the Pier House), it’s a non number. You can’t replace rooms. It’s the highest barrier to entry market in the U.S. because you legally cannot build down there.”

And while he said his investors typically want Ashford to own branded properties, he has no intention of adding a flag to the Pier House. He said the hotel averages 88% occupancy with an average daily rate of more than $300, so “it’s hard to get a sense of how much a brand can add, how much incremental business a brand can add.”

Bennett and Ashford again demonstrated a willingness to try new ideas with the announcement Monday that it is spinning off its highest revenue-per-available-room hotels into a new real estate investment trust to be called Ashford Hospitality Prime. Initially, eight top RevPAR properties owned by Ashford Hospitality Trust will be part of the new REIT. It will have the option to buy the Pier House and plans to acquire upscale, upper-upscale and luxury hotels in gateway cities that generate RevPARs of at least $130.

Bennett wasn’t through trying to poke holes in conventional hotel industry wisdom. Later in the panel discussion at the NYU Conference, he talked about changes he would like to see in the Embassy Suites brand. Ashford’s portfolio of 122 properties includes 14 Embassy Suites.

He said he’s been pushing the brand for 15 years to eliminate free breakfast except on weekends. His rationale: During the week, Embassy attracts mostly corporate travelers who are willing to pay for breakfast or grab something on the way out the door, so why give it away for free? He would keep free breakfasts on weekends because it’s a valued amenity for leisure guests.

*Correction: In the original story, Berman was identifed as principal of PricewaterhouseCoopers' real estate business advisory practice.

